Nikunj,

Thanks for reporting that.  What you&#39;re seeing is a result of how JUnit is
written--once a method is marked @Test, no subclass may take that @Test
status away.  However, I can&#39;t claim that we ever explicitly considered this
case.

Just to be sure I understand what you&#39;re trying to do--it looks like you&#39;d
like to create a subclass of BaseCalculatorTest, and ignore or &quot;de-testify&quot;
the addTest method in that subclass--I assume because that method defines a
contract that the subclass for some reason does not (yet) follow.  Is that
right?

I&#39;d probably achieve that by defining

class ScientificCalculator {

@Test public void addTest(){
  // nothing to see here--add is correct by inspection
}
}

until such time as the appropriate definition of
ScientificCalculator.addTest becomes clear.

To the larger questions, I don&#39;t have a clear intuition.  JUnit community
activate!  What is your expected behavior of ScientificCalculator, as Nikunj
has written below?  Run as a Test, Run Ignored, don&#39;t run at all, or flag as
a configuration error?

   David Saff

